# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cambridge
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday 23 February 1950, and was the first after a full term of a majority Labour Party government.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] It was also the first general election after the abolition of plural voting and university constituencies.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election saw Labour returned to power, but its majority was dramatically reduced from 146 seats to just 5, with a sizeable swing towards the Conservative Party, which gained 90 seats.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Turnout in this general election increased to 83.9%, the highest turnout in a United Kingdom general election under universal suffrage, and represented an increase of 11.1 percentage points from the 72.8% turnout in 1945.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The 1950 general election was also the first to be covered on television.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] (No recording was made of the live broadcast; this was the standard practice at the time.) Richard Dimbleby hosted the BBC coverage of the election, which he would later do again for the 1951, 1955, 1959 and the 1964 general elections.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] On this occasion, Dimbleby was joined in the BBC Alexandra Palace studios by R.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] McCallum, Fellow of Pembroke College, Oxford, and author of *The British General Election of 1945*, and David Butler, research student of Nuffield College.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The programme ran from 10:45 pm until just after 1:00 am.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Another general election was called in the following year, which the Conservatives won, restoring Winston Churchill as Prime Minister after six years in opposition.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour had governed the nation ever since their landslide in 1945.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Britain was confronted with severe economic challenges: the country faced a large national debt, its industries were weakened, and there were many shortages of food and raw materials.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] As a result, the Labour government continued rationing, and austerity was implemented, relying heavily on American loans and the Marshall Plan.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] While these measures were enacted to contain inflationary pressures, the British public suffered a fatigue.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] This prevented the Labour government from implementing some of its ambitious programmes.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Before the general election, major significant changes to the electoral system had occurred, including the abolition of plural voting by the Representation of the People Act 1948, and a major reorganisation of constituencies by the House of Commons (Redistribution of Seats) Act 1949.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Eleven new English seats were created and six were abolished, and there were over 170 major alterations to constituencies across the country.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Prime Minister Clement Attlee planned to call a summer general election.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] However, his Chancellor of the Exchequer, Stafford Cripps, refused to present a budget before a general election.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] As a result, Attlee was persuaded to call a February general election.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Parliament was dissolved on 3 February 1950.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives, having recovered from their landslide election defeat in 1945, accepted the broad framework of the welfare state and nationalisation that had taken place under the Attlee government, which included the National Health Service and the mixed economy.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservative manifesto, *This Is The Road*, accepted the new welfare state's foundations but criticised what it saw as the loss of freedoms and aspirations under Labour, with Churchill claiming Attlee had not "levelled up" but had actually "levelled down".
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The campaign essentially focused on the possible future nationalisation of other sectors and industries, which was opposed by the Conservatives but supported by Labour.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberals essentially viewed the struggle between the two parties on this issue as a class struggle.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Party fielded 475 candidates, more than at any general election since 1929.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Liberal Party leader Clement Davies felt that the party had been at a disadvantage at the 1945 general election when they ran fewer candidates than needed to form a government.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Davies arranged for the cost of running extra candidates to be offset by the party taking out insurance with Lloyd's of London against more than fifty candidates losing their deposits.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] A total of 319 Liberal candidates lost their deposits, a record number until the 2015 general election, when candidates for the Liberal Democrats lost 335 deposits at the general election held in that year.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] In the end, Labour lost 78 seats and its majority was reduced from 146 seats to just 5 seats.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives recovered significantly, seeing a resurgence in their support: they gained 90 seats and saw their vote share improve by 4.3 percentage points.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] With such a slender majority, Attlee had very little room for political manoeuvring, and passing legislation became difficult, with continued austerity and rationing straining Attlee's government from public support.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] As a result, seeking a better mandate, a general election was called the following year.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] However, despite winning the most votes (48.8% and 13,948,385 votes), they lost 20 seats, and Churchill was returned to power with a majority of 17 seats.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Analysis showed that Labour suffered huge losses of seats due to a "revolt of the suburbs", with substantial swings against them among Middle England voters in London, the Home Counties, Essex and Middlesex.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The effects of the Labour government's continued austerity and inflation had a negative effect for middle-income voters, with rationing of basic foods like bread and powdered egg proving incredibly unpopular.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] While campaigning in Leicester, Attlee was met with "catcalls" and chants of "vermin" while Hugh Gaitskell observed there was "a collection of grievances among the lower middle class and middle class" against Labour.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The election began the factionalization of the Labour Party into the Bevanite and Gaitskellite factions.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the general election, Hugh Gaitskell blamed Aneurin Bevan for their party's disappointing performance, which led to a growing rift between the two.
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Prominent personalities entering Parliament in this election included Edward Heath (Bexley), Jo Grimond (Orkney and Shetland), Enoch Powell (Wolverhampton South West), Reginald Maudling (Barnet) and Iain Macleod (Enfield West).
[src:cambridge/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Scottish politician Willie Gallacher lost his West Fife seat to Labour; he was the last MP in Parliament for the Communist Party of Great Britain.
[src:cambridge/1st-century-bc] The **1st century BC**, also known as the **last century BC** and the **last century BCE**, started on the first day of 100 BC and ended on the last day of 1 BC.
[src:cambridge/1st-century-bc] The AD/BC notation does not use a year zero; however, astronomical year numbering does use a zero, as well as a minus sign, so "2 BC" is equal to "year –1".
[src:cambridge/1st-century-bc] In the course of the century, all the remaining independent lands surrounding the Mediterranean Sea were steadily brought under Roman control, being ruled either directly under governors or through puppet kings appointed by Rome.
[src:cambridge/1st-century-bc] The Roman state itself was plunged into civil war several times, finally resulting in the marginalization of its 500-year-old Roman Republic, and the embodiment of total state power in a single man—the Roman emperor.
[src:cambridge/1st-century-bc] The internal turbulence that plagued Rome at this time can be seen as the death throes of the Roman Republic, as it finally gave way to the autocratic ambitions of powerful men like Sulla, Julius Caesar, Mark Antony and Octavian.
[src:cambridge/1st-century-bc] Octavian's ascension to total power as the emperor Augustus is considered to mark the point in history where the Roman Republic ends and the Roman Empire begins.
[src:cambridge/1st-century-bc] Some scholars refer to this event as the Roman Revolution.
[src:cambridge/1st-century-bc] In the eastern mainland, the Han dynasty began to decline and the court of China was in chaos in the latter half of this century.
[src:cambridge/1st-century-bc] Trapped in a difficult situation, the Xiongnu had to begin emigration to the west or attach themselves to the Han.
[src:cambridge/1st-century-bc] See: List of sovereign states in the 1st century BC.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] A census of the population of the United Kingdom is taken every ten years.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The **2011 census** was held in all countries of the UK on 27 March 2011.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] It was the first UK census which could be completed online via the Internet.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics (ONS) is responsible for the census in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) is responsible for the census in Scotland, and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) is responsible for the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is the executive office of the UK Statistics Authority, a non-ministerial department formed in 2008 and which reports directly to Parliament.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS is the UK Government's single largest statistical producer of independent statistics on the UK's economy and society, used to assist the planning and allocation of resources, policy-making and decision-making.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS designs, manages and runs the census in England and Wales.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In its capacity as the national statistics office for the United Kingdom, ONS also compiles and releases census tables for the United Kingdom when the data from England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland are complete.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In the run-up to the census both the main UK political parties expressed concerns about the increasing cost and the value for money of the census, and it was suggested that the 2011 census might be the last decennial census to be taken.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results from the 2011 census, age and sex, and occupied households estimates for England and Wales and Northern Ireland, were released on 16 July 2012.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results for Scotland, and the first UK-wide results, were published on 17 December 2012.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed and specialised data were published from 2013.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Registrar General John Rickman conducted the first census of Great Britain's population, and was responsible for the ten-yearly reports published between 1801 and 1831.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the first 100 years of census-taking the population of England and Wales grew more than threefold, to around 32 million, and that of Scotland, where a separate census has been carried out since 1861, to about 4.5 million.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 1911 onwards rapid social change, scientific breakthroughs, and major world events affected the structure of the population.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] A fire that destroyed census records in 1931, and the declaration of war in 1939, made the 1951 census hugely significant in recording 30 years of change over one of the most turbulent periods in British history.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 1971 census was run by the newly created Office of Population Censuses and Surveys (OPCS), a body formed by the merger of the General Register Office and Government Social Survey.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 1996 the Office for National Statistics (ONS) was formed by merging the Central Statistical Office (CSO), OPCS and the statistics division of the Department of Employment; the first census it ran was in 2001.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2008 the UK Statistics Authority was established as an independent body.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] A population census is a key instrument for assessing the needs of local communities.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] When related to other data sources such as housing or agricultural censuses, or sample surveys, the data becomes even more useful.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Most countries of the world take censuses: the United Nations recommends that countries take a census at least once every ten years.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Twenty-one out of 40 countries in Europe are engaged in the 2010–2011 census round The design for the 2011 census reflected changes in society since 2001 and asked questions to help paint a detailed demographic picture of England and Wales, as it stood on census day, 27 March 2011.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Data collected by the census is used to provide statistical outputs which central government uses to plan and allocate local authority services funding, and which local authorities themselves use to identify and meet the needs of their local communities.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Other organisations that use census data include healthcare organisations, community groups, researchers and businesses.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questionnaires, including people's personal information, are kept confidential for 100 years before being released to the public, providing an important source of information for historical, demographic and genealogy research.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for England and Wales included around 25 million households.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] People could complete and submit their questionnaire online, or fill it in on paper and post it back in a pre-addressed envelope.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Guidance was provided online and through the census helpline.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Completed questionnaires were electronically tracked and field staff followed up with households that did not return a questionnaire.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In these cases field staff delivered and collected questionnaires and, where needed, provided advice or assistance in completing the questionnaire.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] There was a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] As at 27 March 2011 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Failure to return a completed questionnaire could lead to a fine and criminal record.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK, the UK arm of US-based aerospace, defence, security, and technology company Lockheed Martin was awarded the contract to provide services for the census comprising questionnaire printing, a customer contact centre and data capture and processing.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The contract was valued at £150 million, approximately one third of the total £482 million census budget.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Concerns were raised during contract negotiations that the US PATRIOT Act could be used to force Lockheed Martin to reveal census data to US authorities.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several groups called for a boycott of the census over the involvement of Lockheed Martin, including the Stop the War Coalition, and the Christian thinktank Ekklesia.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The groups were concerned about sharing data with a company involved in surveillance and data processing for the CIA and FBI; and also providing funding to an arms company making nuclear missiles and cluster bombs.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Green Party also objected, and campaigned unsuccessfully to stop Lockheed Martin getting the contract, although no decision was made about whether or not to call for a boycott.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Census Alert campaign group also decided against calling for a boycott.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy said a boycott would be counter-productive, as the census is used to distribute funding to local services.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy reports that a council may lose £22,000 over 10 years for each person who does not complete the census.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The census for England and Wales was trialled in 135,000 households in Lancaster, the London Borough of Newham and Anglesey on 11 October 2009.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] A test was also carried out in Birmingham at the same time.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questions for the 2011 census were the same as those trialled in the 2009 Census Rehearsal.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Order for the 2011 Census (including the proposed question topics, census date and who should complete the questionnaire) was laid before Parliament in October 2009 and was approved by Parliament and became law in December 2009.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Capita Group was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 35,000 temporary ONS workers who worked as field staff for the 2011 census.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The total cost of the 2011 census in England and Wales over the period from 2004/05 to 2015/16 is estimated to be £482 million.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] This is more than twice the £210m spent on the 2001 census.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] This breaks down to a cost of 87 pence per person, per year (over the life of the census – ten years).
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] "The cost equates to about 87p a year per person, demonstrating excellent value for money.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The per capita costs in the UK are less than for many other European countries that carry out similar censuses.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In summary, this census will meet crucial requirements for statistical information that Government and others cannot do without." Minister of State, Cabinet Office (Angela E.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Both the main UK political parties had expressed concerns about the rising costs and value of a ten-yearly census, and on coming into office the UK coalition government had gone as far as suggesting that the 2011 census might be the last of its kind.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In July 2010 the UK government asked ONS to explore other methods of measuring the population.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 the three national statistics bodies, ONS, GROS and NISRA set up a co-ordinated research project known as Beyond 2011.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The project reported its findings in March 2014 and recommended that a UK-wide census in 2021 should take place, and that better use should be made of other demographic data sources.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The general style of the questionnaire was similar to that of the 2001 census.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal questionnaire was released in 2009.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several new identity and status options were included for the first time.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2001 only 38 people were reported to have been prosecuted for refusing to complete a questionnaire.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 those who refused to complete the census questionnaire or included false information could face a fine of up to £1,000.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] A team of compliance staff were recruited to follow up by visiting those householders who refused to complete a questionnaire or where their questionnaire was not returned or completed correctly.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Advertising promoted the notion of how the UK 2011 census would help to shape Britain's future in areas such as healthcare and education.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] TV adverts, for example, depicted Origami, in census colours, forming objects including school computers and buses.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] A short sentence under the census logo informed the viewer that the census was a duty that must be undertaken.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 7 April 2011 advertising focused on reminding people to complete and return by post or submit online.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] A question about the number of bedrooms a household has, as well as the names, gender and birth dates of any overnight guests was criticised as "bedroom snooping" by the Conservative Party in opposition.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Although some 37,000 people recorded their identity as Cornish by manually writing it on the form in the 2001 census, no tick-box was provided in 2011 to select Cornish as a White British national identity, despite campaigns.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] As a consequence, posters were created by the census organisation and Cornwall Council which advised residents of how they could identify themselves as Cornish by writing it in the ethnicity, national identity and main language sections.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, people could record Cornwall as their country of birth.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the consultation on the 2011 census the British Humanist Association raised several concerns about question 20, "What is your religion?".
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA argued it was a leading question, and suggested that it should be phrased as two questions, "Do you have a religion?" and "If so, what is it?".
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] It contended that by placing the religion question near the ethnicity question it would encourage some responders to associate religion with cultural identity.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA also ran adverts during March 2011 encouraging the use of the 'no religion' box in the questionnaire.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland had 59 questions in total.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] 14 were about the household and its accommodation and 45 questions were for each individual member of the household to complete.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The rehearsal was held on Sunday 11 October 2009 in two areas, Derriaghy and Moy & Benburb, covering approximately 5,000 households.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland costing around £21.8 million over the six-year period 2008–2014.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Over the ten-year cycle the cost is expected to be about £25 million.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, a wholly owned subsidiary of information technology company CACI was contracted to gather information.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] CACI "provided interrogators who worked at Abu Ghraib prison at the height of the prisoner abuse scandal".
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 Scotland census asked 13 household questions and up to 35 questions for each individual.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Plans were rehearsed in west Edinburgh and Lewis and Harris.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census was the first to include a question asking about the ability to read, write and understand the Scots language alongside the question for ability in Scottish Gaelic and English languages.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Responsibility for the release of data from the 2011 census is split between the Office for National Statistics (ONS) for England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) for Scotland and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The ONS announced in March the release plan for the results of the 2011 census which stated in July 2012.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA made a similar announcement with identical release plan.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In June 2012 GROS advised on its release plan which commences in December 2012.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The releases will comprise data sets enabling the standard comparison with previous census data reports as well as over a hundred new data sets based on the new questions asked in the 2011 census.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA, ONS and GROS each publish a schedule stating what documents they will release and when.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Those documents are called a "prospectus".
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each prospectus is not fixed, but changes as schedules are changed or documents are late.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The prospectuses are linked to in the table below.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is responsible for publishing United Kingdom wide 2011 census data.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] These are co-ordinated releases coinciding with data published by the three national statistical authorities.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population data including data for males and females for the United Kingdom and revised estimates England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population numbers (rounded), by five-year age bands, sex and densities and household sata at national and local authority level.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates (unrounded) by single year of age and sex for the UK and all local authorities (or equivalent) in the UK, along with UK historic population pyramids (1951–2011).
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 1 – Census Profiles; Population, People and Places, Health and Social Care, Travel and Transport.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] National and Local Authority geographies.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 2 – Census Profiles; Qualifications and Labour Market.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 3 – Multivariate, Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for: Living arrangements; Household composition; and Accommodation type.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] A series of further releases, subsequent to the four main releases of 2011 Census statistics including migration tables, workplace tables, detailed religion and ethnic group tables, and statistics relating to alternative population bases.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Specialist products would include:- Small population groups; microdata; flow data (also known as origin-destination statistics).
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] It is also suggested that data organised around alternative population bases may be produced.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The original plans of the ONS, covering England and Wales, confirmed that there would be four stages of data release starting in July 2012 and running until October 2013.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] This was increased to five stages in October 2013.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] A detailed commentary accompanies each release along with relevant reference materials.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally there will be graphic visualisations providing further clarification and comparison between different data sets and comparison over time using data from earlier censuses.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] There will also be more specialist reports and products.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Certain data bases will also be produced in the Welsh language.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick univariate (single parameter) statistics based on output levels, with release based on geography.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] (e.g. local authority, wards and parish/ community) tabulated by population count and percentages and accessible by post code.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key Statistics for local authorities in England and Wales comprising data which adds detail to the population estimates published in July 2012.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] It includes population information on international migration, age, ethnicity, national identity, health, housing and religion.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Wales, there is data on the Welsh language and population data on unitary authorities.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for Output Areas (OAs) and for wards.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Background information covering families, general health and disability, unpaid care, language, occupation and industry, qualifications and economic activity.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics for postcode sectors, health areas and Welsh Government devolved constituencies, and the key statistics for national parks in England and Wales, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for non-UK short-term residents in England and Wales and quick statistics for England and Wales on national identity, passports held and country of birth, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed cross tabulation of data topics: Migration; ethnicity, identity, language and religion; health; and Welsh tables.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed Characteristics tables for the themes of demography and families at local authority, MSOA and ward level.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] English language proficiency for regions, local authorities, 2011 Census Merged Wards and MSOAs in England and Wales.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first Local Characteristics tables for the topics of ethnicity, identity, language and religion for Output Areas, unitary and local authorities and regions.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics tables for the topics of health and unpaid care for Output Areas.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Follow up to Release 3.2b on 12 July 2013.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristic Tables for the topic of migration for Output Areas.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics on travel to work and car and van availability for Output Areas.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the six main releases phases further supplementary, smaller scale and specialist releases including; Small population groups, Microdata (teaching files, safeguarded files and secure files), Origin-destination data, and Alternate population bases.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Northern Ireland were set out by the NISRA.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release phases are closely synchronised with those of the ONS for England and Wales with some marginal variations to allow for local administrative arrangements.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex for Local Government Districts, etc.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Household number and size by geographic units.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key statistics for NI and Local Government Districts etc.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Quick statistics for all geographies and population and household estimates for lower geographies.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI-wide and all local authority and other geographies (including religion, identity and health).
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI (including ethnicity, country of birth and language).
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Remaining detailed characteristics for NI including labour market and housing.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] All outstanding detailed characteristics for the remaining geographic areas.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate local characteristic tables and detailed themes around: economic activity; country of birth; occupation; and unpaid care.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Scotland were set out by the GROS Release phase dates are partly in sync with those of the other UK constituent country statistical authorities, however the first release was scheduled for six months after the first releases by the other authorities.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Consequently, release of UK-wide data has been scheduled so as to coincide with release plans for Scotland's Census releases.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates, based on resident households, communal establishments and age bands.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Estimates of the usually resident population of Scotland rounded to the nearest thousand, broken down by age and sex.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] An estimate of the total population in each council area, rounded to nearest thousand.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates by five-year age bands and sex for Scotland and each council area.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population and household changes since 2001 census.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population dependency ratios for Scotland and each council area.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] First release of unrounded population estimates and household communal establishment numbers, by single year of age and sex.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] (First published as rounded data in December 2012 and March 2013).
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics; Census Profiles; headcounts and geography products.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Comprising; Estimates by postcode and geography products.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] This release will represent the start of the dissemination of detailed census statistics for small areas.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for marriage and civil partnership, ethnicity, religion, language proficiency, country of birth and national identity, heath (excluding long-term health), age, arrival in UK, population and households, housing and accommodation, car and van ownership.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: Scotland, Council Areas and Health Boards.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Education and Labour Market.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All output areas and Data Zones.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Also the key and quick statistics for the remaining geographies of the topics covered in Release 2a.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Living Arrangements and Travel to Work Methods.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All levels of census geographies.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate statistics, comprising a combination of; age, sex, resident type, ethnic group, economic activity, general health and provision of unpaid care, country of birth, and occupation.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for Qualifications, Employment and Economic Activity, Travel for Work and Study.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables including; Travel to Work, Household, Qualifications and Long-term Health, Social Status and Economic Activity.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The United Kingdom Statistics Authority is responsible for coordinating the release of census data by the devolved statistics authorities.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] It publishes UK-wide census data results via the Office for National Statistics (ONS) site.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The UK Data Service provides a central point of reference for all country-specific census data releases via its Learning Hub site.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Primary responsibility for country-specific 2011 census data rests with the statistical authorities for each of the UK's constituent countries.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each authority has at least one dedicated central source from which data can be downloaded or ordered.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] For England and Wales the ONS provides the access to primary data via its 2011 census siteArchived 29 January 2016 at the UK Government Web Archive.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, data organised by local authority or post code is available on the Neighbourhood Statistics Archived 20 October 2010 at the Wayback Machine site, and nomis, a source of detailed census results which can be assembled into bespoke data sets.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Scotland the General Registrar Office for Scotland (GROS) part of National Records of Scotland (NRS) to maintain access via its Scotlands Census site, and for Northern Ireland the Statistics and Research Authority (NISRA) uses the Northern Ireland Neighbourhood Information Service (NINIS).
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The format of all the pre-defined statistical tables is standardised as far as practical across the publishing authorities.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] Since the 2001 UK census the naming conventions for the tables have been revised following research into the approaches adopted by other census publishing bodies around the world.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] The statistical authorities are also making available bulk data in Comma-separated values (CSV) file format which can be downloaded from online data warehouse facilities.
[src:cambridge/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the standard releases and online bulk access the statistical authorities provide a commissioned data service whereby other data configurations can be purchased, under license, by customers and will subsequently be made freely available to other users.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on 7 May 2015 to elect 650 members of Parliament (MPs) to the House of Commons.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative Party, led by Prime Minister David Cameron, won an unexpected majority victory of 10 seats; they had been leading a coalition government with the Liberal Democrats.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It was the last general election to be held before the UK voted to leave the European Union (EU) in June 2016.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It was the first of three general elections to be held under the rules of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Local elections took place in most areas of England on the same day and is to date the most recent general election to coincide with local elections.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Opinion polls and political commentators had widely predicted that the election would result in a second consecutive hung parliament whose composition would be similar to the one elected at the previous general election in 2010.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Potential coalitions and agreements between parties were intensively discussed; as a result, smaller parties received much more attention during the campaign than in previous UK elections.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, opinion polls underestimated the Conservatives, as they won 330 of the 650 seats and 36.9 per cent of the vote, giving them a small overall majority.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The opposition Labour Party, led by Ed Miliband, saw a small increase in vote share to 30.4 per cent, but it returned 232 MPs, 26 fewer than in 2010 and their fewest since the 1987 general election, when it had 229 MPs.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour lost significant ground in Scotland to the Scottish National Party (SNP) who enjoyed a huge surge, winning 56 of the 59 Scottish seats, becoming the third-largest party in the House of Commons and the largest party in Scotland, knocking Labour from the status which it had held since 1964.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats, junior coalition partners led by Deputy Prime Minister Nick Clegg, suffered heavy losses, losing 49 of their 57 seats.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Returning just eight MPs, it was their worst result since 1970 when its predecessors party, the Liberal Party, returned six MPs.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Cabinet ministers Vince Cable, Ed Davey, and Danny Alexander lost their seats, whilst Clegg only narrowly held his own seat.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The UK Independence Party (UKIP) received 12.6 per cent of the vote, displacing the Liberal Democrats as the third-placed party in terms of popular vote, but won only one seat: Clacton, which they had gained at a by-election six months earlier.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They failed to retain their other seat gained in a by-election, Rochester and Strood, and the party's leader, Nigel Farage, ran in South Thanet but did not win the seat.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Green Party of England and Wales won its highest vote share unto that point at 3.8%, and their only MP, Caroline Lucas, retained her seat, Brighton Pavilion.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Following the election, Miliband and Clegg resigned their leaderships.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Jeremy Corbyn succeeded Miliband as Leader of the Labour Party, while Tim Farron succeeded Clegg as Leader of the Liberal Democrats.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP began a nine-year domination of Scottish Westminster seats.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Charles Kennedy, who served as the leader of the Liberal Democrats from 1999 to 2006, made his last public appearance during the election campaign, in which he lost his seat; he died on 1 June 2015.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Notable MPs who retired at this election included former prime minister and Labour leader Gordon Brown, former Chancellor of the Exchequer Alistair Darling, former leader of the opposition and Conservative leader William Hague, and former leader of the Liberal Democrats Menzies Campbell.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Another future prime minister and Conservative leader, Boris Johnson, who had previously left Parliament in 2008 so he could serve as the mayor of London, returned to Parliament as MP for Uxbridge and South Ruislip.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011 led to the dissolution of the 55th Parliament on 30 March 2015 and the scheduling of the election on 7 May.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There were local elections on the same day in all of England, with the exception of Greater London.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] No elections were scheduled to take place in Scotland, Wales, or Northern Ireland.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] All British, Irish, and Commonwealth citizens over the age of 18 and residing in the UK who were not in prison or a mental hospital or a fugitive on the date of the election were permitted to vote.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In British general elections, voting takes place in all constituencies in the United Kingdom to elect Members of Parliament to the House of Commons, the lower house of Parliament in the UK.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Each constituency elects one MP using the first-past-the-post voting system.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] If one party obtains a majority (326) of the 650 seats, then that party is entitled to form the government.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] If no party has a majority, then there is what is known as a hung parliament.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In this case, the options for forming the Government are either a minority government (where one party governs alone despite not having the majority of the seats) or a coalition government (where one party governs alongside party in order to get a majority of seats).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The next boundary review was set to take place in 2018, so the 2015 general election was contested using the same constituencies and boundaries as in 2010.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Of the 650 constituencies, 533 were in England, 59 were in Scotland, 40 were in Wales and 18 were in Northern Ireland.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In addition, the 2011 Act mandated a referendum in 2011 on changing from the first-past-the-post voting system to an alternative vote system for general elections.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition government agreed to holding a referendum.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The referendum was held in May 2011 and resulted in the retention of the existing voting system.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Before the previous general election the Liberal Democrats had pledged to change the voting system, and the Labour Party had pledged to hold a referendum on any such change.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives, however, promised to keep the first-past-the-post system, but to reduce the number of constituencies to 600.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Liberal Democrats' plan was to reduce the number of MPs to 500, and for them to be elected using a proportional vote system.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Government increased the amount of money that parties and candidates were allowed to spend on campaigning during the election by 23%, a move decided against the advice of the Electoral Commission.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The election saw the first cap on spending by parties in individual constituencies during the 100 days before Parliament's dissolution on 30 March: £30,700, plus a per-voter allowance of 9p in county constituencies and 6p in borough seats.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] An additional voter allowance of more than £8,700 is available after the dissolution of Parliament.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In total, parties spent £31.1m in the 2010 general election, of which the Conservative Party spent 53%, the Labour Party spent 25% and the Liberal Democrats 15%.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was also the first UK general election to use individual rather than household voter registration.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] An election is called following the dissolution of the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The 2015 general election was the first to be held under the provisions of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Prior to this, the power to dissolve Parliament was a royal prerogative, exercised by the sovereign on the advice of the prime minister.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Under the provisions of the Septennial Act 1715, as amended by the Parliament Act 1911, an election had to be announced on or before the fifth anniversary of the beginning of the previous parliament, barring exceptional circumstances.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Prior to the 2010 general election, Labour and the Liberal Democrats pledged to introduce fixed-term elections.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] As part of the Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition agreement, the Cameron ministry agreed to support legislation for fixed-term Parliaments, with the date of the next general election being 7 May 2015.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This resulted in the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011, which removed the prime minister's power to advise the monarch to call an early election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Act only permits an early dissolution if Parliament votes for one by a two-thirds supermajority, or if a majority of MPs pass a vote of no confidence and no new government is subsequently formed within 14 days.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, the prime minister had the power, by order made by Statutory Instrument under section 1(5) of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011, to fix the polling day to be up to two months later than 7 May 2015.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Such a Statutory Instrument must be approved by each House of Parliament.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Under section 14 of the Electoral Registration and Administration Act 2013, the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011 was amended to extend the period between the dissolution of Parliament and the following general election polling day from 17 to 25 working days.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This had the effect of moving forward the date of the dissolution of the Parliament to 30 March 2015.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] While at the previous election there had been a record 149 MPs not standing for re-election, the 2015 election saw 89 MPs standing down.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Out of these MPs, 37 were Conservatives, 37 were Labour, 10 were Liberal Democrats, 3 were Independents, 1 was Sinn Féin and 1 was Plaid Cymru.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The highest-profile members of parliament leaving were: Gordon Brown, the former Prime Minister, and William Hague, the former Leader of the Conservative Party and Leader of the Opposition.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Alongside Brown and Hague, 17 former cabinet ministers stood down at the election, including Stephen Dorrell, Jack Straw, Alistair Darling, David Blunkett, Sir Malcolm Rifkind and Dame Tessa Jowell.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The highest-profile Liberal Democrat to stand down was their former leader Sir Menzies Campbell, while the longest-serving MP, Sir Peter Tapsell, also retired, having served as an MP continuously since 1966, or for 49 years.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 9 April 2015, the deadline for standing for the general election, there were 464 political parties registered with the Electoral Commission.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Candidates who did not belong to a party were either labelled as an Independent or not labelled at all.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative Party and the Labour Party had been the two biggest parties since 1922.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Every prime minister to serve since 1935 had been the leader of the Conservatives or Labour.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats had been the third largest party in the UK for many years; but as described by various political commentators, other parties had risen relative to the Liberal Democrats since the 2010 election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The BBC's guidelines were similar but removed UKIP from their list of major parties, and instead stated that UKIP should be given "appropriate levels of coverage in output to which the largest parties contribute and, on some occasions, similar levels of coverage".
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Seven parties participated in the election leadership debates: Conservative, Labour, Liberal Democrat, UKIP, SNP, PC and Green.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Northern Ireland's political parties were not included in any debates, despite the DUP, a party based in Northern Ireland, being the fourth largest party in the UK going into the election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Several parties operate in specific regions only.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Dozens of minor parties stood in this election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition stood 135 candidates and was the only minor party to have more than forty candidates.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Respect Party, who came into the election with one MP who was elected at the 2012 Bradford West by-election, stood four candidates.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The British National Party, who finished fifth with 1.9% of the vote and stood 338 candidates at the 2010 general election, stood only eight candidates this year following a collapse in their support.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Seven hundred fifty-three other candidates stood at the general election, including Independents and candidates from other parties.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Smaller parties in Northern Ireland included the Traditional Unionist Voice, who won no seats at this election but had one member of the Northern Ireland Assembly, the Conservatives and UKIP (both are major parties in the rest of the UK, but are minor parties here).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Smaller parties in Scotland include the Scottish Libertarian Party, but none of the smaller parties make much of an impact in general elections in Scotland.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Wales has a number of smaller parties which, again, do not tend to make much impact in the general elections.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In 2015, the Labour Party continued to dominate Welsh politics at the general elections.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Coalitions have been rare in the United Kingdom, because the system of first-past-the-post voting has usually led to one party winning an overall majority in the Commons.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, with the outgoing Government being a coalition and with opinion polls not showing a large or consistent lead for any one party, there was much discussion about possible post-election coalitions or other arrangements, such as confidence and supply agreements.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Some UK political parties that only stand in part of the country have reciprocal relationships with parties standing in other parts of the country.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 17 March 2015 the Democratic Unionist Party and the Ulster Unionist Party agreed an election pact, whereby the DUP would not stand candidates in Fermanagh and South Tyrone (where Michelle Gildernew, the Sinn Féin candidate, won by only four votes in 2010) and in Newry and Armagh.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In return the UUP would stand aside in Belfast East and Belfast North.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SDLP rejected a similar pact suggested by Sinn Féin to try to ensure that an agreed nationalist would win that constituency.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The DUP also called on voters in Scotland to support whichever pro-Union candidate was best placed to beat the SNP.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The deadline for parties and individuals to file candidate nomination papers to the acting returning officer (and the deadline for candidates to withdraw) was 4 p.m. on 9 April 2015.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The total number of candidates was 3,971; the second-highest number in history, slightly down from the record 4,150 candidates at the last election in 2010.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There were a record number of female candidates standing in terms of both absolute numbers and percentage of candidates: 1,020 (26.1%) in 2015, up from 854 (21.1%) in 2010.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The proportion of female candidates for major parties ranged from 41% of Alliance Party candidates to 12% of UKIP candidates.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] According to UCL's Parliamentary Candidates UK project the major parties had the following percentages of black and ethnic minority candidates: the Conservatives 11%, the Liberal Democrats 10%, Labour 9%, UKIP 6%, the Greens 4%.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The average age of the candidates for the seven major parties was 45.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The youngest candidates were all aged 18: Solomon Curtis (Labour, Wealden); Niamh McCarthy (Independent, Liverpool Wavertree); Michael Burrows (UKIP, Inverclyde); Declan Lloyd (Labour, South East Cornwall); and Laura-Jane Rossington (Communist Party, Plymouth Sutton and Devonport).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The oldest candidate was Doris Osen, 84, of the Elderly Persons' Independent Party (EPIC), who contested Ilford North.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Other candidates aged over 80 included three long-serving Labour MPs standing for re-election: Sir Gerald Kaufman (aged 84; Manchester Gorton), Dennis Skinner (aged 83; Bolsover) and David Winnick (aged 81; Walsall North).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Following his re-election, Kaufman became Father of the House, an honorary title he held until his death in early 2017.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Several candidates, including two each for Labour and UKIP, were suspended from their respective parties after nominations were closed.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Independent candidate Ronnie Carroll died after nominations were closed.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In late 2014, six months before the election, the Conservatives decided to target Lib Dem seats as well as defending their own seats and targeting Conservative–Labour marginals, which ultimately contributed to their victory.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In 2015 David Cameron launched the Conservative formal campaign in Chippenham on 30 March.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Throughout the campaign the Conservatives played on fears of a Labour–SNP coalition following the Scottish independence referendum the year before.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Labour campaign was launched on 27 March at Olympic Park in London.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Ed Miliband's EdStone was a major feature of the campaign which was covered by the media.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Deputy Leader of the Labour Party Harriet Harman embarked on a pink bus tour as part of her Woman to Woman campaign.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative manifesto committed to "a straight in-out referendum on our membership of the European Union by the end of 2017".
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour did not support this, but did commit to an EU membership referendum if any further powers were transferred to the European Union.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Lib Dems also supported the Labour position, but explicitly supported the UK's continuing membership of the EU.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The election was the first following the 2014 Scottish independence referendum.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] None of the three major party manifestos supported a second referendum and the Conservative manifesto stated that "the question of Scotland's place in the United Kingdom is now settled".
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In the run-up to the election, David Cameron coined the phrase "Carlisle principle" for the idea that checks and balances are required to ensure that devolution to Scotland has no adverse effects on other parts of the United Kingdom.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The phrase references a fear that Carlisle, being the English town closest to the Scottish border, could be affected economically by preferential tax rates in Scotland.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The deficit, who was responsible for it and plans to deal with it were a major theme of the campaign.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] While some smaller parties opposed austerity, the Conservatives, Labour, Liberal Democrats, UKIP and the Greens all supported some further cuts, albeit to different extents.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Conservative campaigning sought to blame the deficit on the previous Labour government.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour, in return, sought to establish their fiscal responsibility.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] With the Conservatives also making several spending commitments (e.g., on the NHS), commentators talked of the two main parties' 'political crossdressing', each trying to campaign on the other's traditional territory.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was also associated with a rise in multi-party politics, with increased support for UKIP, the SNP and the Greens.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The question of what the different parties would do in the likely event of an inconclusive result dominated much of the campaign.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Smaller parties focused on the power this would bring them in negotiations; Labour and the Conservatives both insisted that they were working towards winning overall majorities, while they were also reported to be preparing for the possibility of a second election later in the year.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In practice, Labour were prepared to make a 'broad' offer to the Liberal Democrats in the event of a hung parliament.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Most predictions saw Labour as having more potential support in parliament than the Conservatives, with several parties, notably the SNP, having committed to preventing a Conservative government.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives claimed a hung parliament with Labour as the largest party would result in a 'coalition of chaos', and David Cameron tweeted that the electoral choice was one between 'stable and strong government with me, or chaos with Ed Miliband'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Due to the substantial political turmoil in Britain in the years following the 2015 election, the tweet became infamous.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Conservative campaigning sought to highlight what they described as the dangers of a minority Labour administration supported by the SNP.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This proved effective at dominating the agenda of the campaign and at motivating voters to support them.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The surprise Conservative victory was 'widely put down to the success of the anti-Labour/SNP warnings', according to the BBC and other media commentators.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour, in reaction, produced ever stronger denials that they would cooperate with the SNP after the election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives and Lib Dems both also rejected the idea of a coalition with the SNP.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was particularly notable for Labour, to whom the SNP had previously offered support: their manifesto stated that "the SNP will never put the Tories into power.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Instead, if there is an anti-Tory majority after the election, we will offer to work with other parties to keep the Tories out".
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] SNP leader Nicola Sturgeon later confirmed in the Scottish leaders' debate on STV that she was prepared to 'help make Ed Miliband prime minister'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, on 26 April, Miliband ruled out a confidence and supply arrangement with the SNP too.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Miliband's comments suggested to many that he was aiming to form a minority government.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats said that they would talk first to whichever party won the most seats.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Both Labour and the Liberal Democrats ruled out coalitions with UKIP.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Ruth Davidson, leader of the Scottish Conservatives, asked about a deal with UKIP in the Scottish leaders' debate, replied: 'No deals with UKIP.' She continued that her preference and the Prime Minister's preference in a hung parliament was for a minority Conservative government.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] UKIP said they could have supported a minority Conservative government through a confidence and supply arrangement in return for a referendum on EU membership before Christmas 2015.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They also spoke of the DUP joining UKIP in this arrangement.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] UKIP and the DUP said they would work together in Parliament.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The DUP welcomed the possibility of a hung parliament and the influence that this would bring them.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The party's deputy leader, Nigel Dodds, said they could work with the Conservatives or Labour, but that they were 'not interested in a full-blown coalition government'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Their leader, Peter Robinson, said that the DUP would talk first to whichever party wins the most seats.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The DUP said they wanted, for their support, a commitment to 2% defence spending, a referendum on EU membership, and a reversal of the under-occupation penalty.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They opposed the SNP being involved in government.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The UUP also indicated that they would not work with the SNP if it wanted another independence referendum in Scotland.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Additionally, issues were raised about the continued existence of the BBC – as the DUP, UKIP and Conservatives had made a number of statements criticising the institution – as well as support for same-sex marriage.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Plaid Cymru, the SNP, and the Green Party of England and Wales all ruled out working with the Conservatives, and agreed to work together 'wherever possible' to counter austerity.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Each would also make it a condition of any agreement with Labour that Trident nuclear weapons were not replaced; the Green Party of England and Wales stated that 'austerity is a red line'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Both Plaid Cymru and the Green Party stated a preference for a confidence and supply arrangement with Labour, rather than a coalition.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The leader of the SDLP, Alasdair McDonnell, said 'we will be the left-of-centre backbone of a Labour administration' and that 'the SDLP will categorically refuse to support David Cameron and the Conservative Party'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Sinn Féin reiterated their abstentionist stance.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In the event, the Conservatives did, against expectations, secure a small overall majority, rendering most of the speculation and positioning moot.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The first series of televised leaders' debates in the United Kingdom was held in the previous election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Returning major party leaders Cameron and Clegg participated, as did then-prime minister Gordon Brown, who did not seek re-election in his constituency in 2015.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Following much debate and various proposals, a seven-way ITV debate with the leaders of Labour, the Conservatives, Liberal Democrats, UKIP, Greens, SNP and Plaid Cymru was held on 2 April. with a series of other debates involving some of the parties.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A five-way BBC debate with the Labour, UKIP, Green, SNP and Plaid Cymru leaders was held on 16 April.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The other parties criticised Cameron's absence from the debate.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Finally, a *Question Time* special was broadcast on 30 April, featuring Cameron, Miliband and Clegg.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Other party leaders – Sturgeon, Wood and Farage – were given about half an hour to answer questions from an audience in *Ask ...* programs.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] *Ask Nicola Sturgeon,* *Ask Leanne Wood* and *Ask Nigel Farage* were broadcast on BBC1 afterwards.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Various newspapers, organisations and individuals endorsed parties or individual candidates for the election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Despite speculation that 2015 would be the 'social media election', traditional media, particularly broadcast media, remained more influential than new digital platforms.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A majority of the public (62%) reported that TV coverage had been most influential for informing them during the election period, especially televised debates between politicians.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Newspapers were next most influential, with the *Daily Mail* influencing people's opinions most (30%), followed by *The Guardian* (21%) and *The Times* (20%).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Online, major media outlets—like BBC News, newspaper websites, and Sky News—were most influential.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Social media was regarded less influential than radio and conversations with friends and family.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] During the campaign, TV news coverage was dominated by horse race journalism, focusing on the how close Labour and the Conservatives were according to the polls, and speculation on possible coalition outcomes.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There were concerns this 'meta-coverage' was pushing policy issues to the sideline.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Policy received less than half of election news airtime across all five main TV broadcasters (BBC, ITV, Channel 4, Channel 5 and Sky) during the first five weeks of the campaign.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On TV, these topics made up 43% of all election news coverage; within the papers, nearly a third (31%) of all election-related articles were on the economy alone.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Less attention was given to policy areas that might have been problematic for the Conservatives, like the NHS or housing (policy topics favoured by Labour) or immigration (favoured by UKIP).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Reflecting on analysis carried out during the election campaign period, David Deacon of Loughborough University's Communication Research Centre said there was 'aggressive partisanship [in] many section of the national press' which could be seen especially in the 'Tory press'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] According to Bart Cammaerts of the Media and Communications Department at the London School of Economics, during the campaign 'almost all newspapers were extremely pro-Conservative and rabidly anti-Labour'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] 57.5% of the daily newspapers backed the Conservatives, 11.7% Labour, 4.9% UKIP, and 1.4% backed a continuation of the incumbent Conservative – Liberal Democrat coalition government; 66% of Sunday national newspapers backed the Conservatives.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Of newspaper front-page lead stories, the Conservatives received 80 positive splashes and 26 negative; Labour received 30 positive against 69 negative.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Print media was hostile towards Labour at levels 'not seen since the 1992 general election', when Neil Kinnock was 'attacked hard and hit below the belt repeatedly'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Roy Greenslade described the newspaper coverage of Labour as 'relentless ridicule'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Of the leader columns in *The Sun*, 95% were anti-Labour.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP also received substantial negative press in English newspapers: of the 59 leader columns about the SNP during the election, one was positive.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The *Daily Mail* ran a headline suggesting SNP leader Nicola Sturgeon was 'the most dangerous woman in Britain' and, at other times, called her a 'glamorous power-dressing imperatrix' and said that she 'would make Hillary Clinton look human'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] While the Scottish edition of *The Sun* encouraged people north of the border to vote for the SNP, the English edition encouraged people to vote for the Conservatives in order to "stop the SNP running the country".
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The negative coverage of the SNP increased towards the end of the election campaign.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] At times, the Conservatives worked closely with newspapers to co-ordinate their news coverage.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] For example, *The Daily Telegraph* printed a letter purportedly sent directly to the paper from 5,000 small business owners; the letter had been organised by the Conservatives and prepared at Conservative Campaign Headquarters.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] According to researchers at Cardiff University and Loughborough University, TV news agendas focused on Conservative campaign issues partly because of editorial choices to report on news originally broken in the right-leaning press but not that broken in the left-leaning press.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Researchers also found that the most airtime was given to Conservative politicians, especially in Channel 4's and Channel 5's news coverage, where they received more than a third of speaking time.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Only ITV gave more airtime to Labour spokespeople (26.9% compared with 25.1% for the Conservatives).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Airtime given to the two main political leaders, Cameron (22.4%) and Miliband (20.9%), was more balanced than that given to their parties.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Smaller parties – especially the SNP – received unprecedented levels of media coverage because of speculation about a minority or coalition government.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The five most prominent politicians were David Cameron (Con) (15% of TV and press appearances), Ed Miliband (Lab) (14.7%), Nick Clegg (Lib Dem) (6.5%), Nicola Sturgeon (SNP) (5.7%), and Nigel Farage (UKIP) (5.5%).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, according to analysts from Loughborough University Communication Research Centre: 'The big winners of the media coverage were the Conservatives.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Other than politicians, 'business sources' were the most frequently quoted in the media.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On the other hand, trade union representatives, for example, received very little coverage, with business representatives receiving seven times more coverage than unions.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Former prime minister Tony Blair was also in the top ten most prominent politicians (equal 9th), warning against the possibility of the UK leaving the EU.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Throughout most of the 2010–15 Parliament, Labour held a consistent polling lead over the Conservatives.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Labour overtook the Conservatives at the end of 2010 – benefiting from a collapse in Liberal Democrat support – holding a small lead throughout 2011.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Following a brief tightening in early 2012, Labour opened up a wider lead as the Conservatives suffered a slump, partially due to rising UKIP support.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] UKIP passed the Liberal Democrats – whose ratings were still stagnant – as the third-placed party at the start of 2013.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Following this, Labour's lead dipped a little as UKIP also gained support from them.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Labour's lead gradually declined throughout 2014, largely attributed to increases in support for the SNP and the Green Party, as the Conservatives remained relatively level.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Liberal Democrat support continued to fall, dipping into single-digits.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] UKIP won the most seats at the European elections in June 2014, receiving 26.6% of the vote.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Though their support in the polls for Westminster never reached this level, it did rise up to over 15% through the year.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Scottish independence referendum was also held in 2014; despite the 'no' vote winning, support for the Scottish National Party rose quickly after the referendum.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Wales, where polls were less frequent, the decline in Labour's lead was smaller, while UKIP and Plaid Cymru made gains.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Early 2015 saw the gap between Labour and the Conservatives continue to tighten, and by the start of the campaign at the end of March, the two parties were in a dead heat.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Polling during the campaign itself remained relatively static, with the Labour and Conservative parties both polling between 33 and 34% and neither able to establish a consistent lead.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Support for the Green Party and UKIP showed slight drops, while Liberal Democrat support slightly rose up to around 9%.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Scotland, support for the SNP continued to grow with polling figures in late March reaching 54%, with the Labour vote continuing to decline accordingly, while Labour retained their (reduced) lead in Wales.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The final polls showed a mixture of small Conservative and Labour leads and ties with both between 31 and 36%, UKIP on 11–16%, the Lib Dems on 8–10%, the Greens on 4–6%, and the SNP on 4–5% of the national vote.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The first-past-the-post system used in UK general elections means that the number of seats won is not exactly relative to vote share.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Thus, several approaches were used to convert polling data and other information into seat predictions.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The table below lists some of the predictions.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Some predictions cover Northern Ireland, with its distinct political culture, while others do not.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Parties are sorted by current number of seats in the House of Commons.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] An exit poll, collected by Ipsos MORI and GfK on behalf of the BBC, ITN and Sky News, was published at 10 pm at the end of voting.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] This predicted the Conservatives to be 10 seats short of an absolute majority, although with the 5 predicted Sinn Féin MPs not taking their seats, it was likely to be enough to govern – although Sinn Féin eventually only won 4 seats.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The exit poll was markedly different from pre-election polls, which had been fairly consistent; this led many pundits and MPs to speculate that the exit poll was inaccurate, and that the final result would have the two main parties closer to each other.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Former Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown vowed to "eat his hat" and former Labour "spin doctor" Alastair Campbell promised to "eat his kilt" if the exit poll was right.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] As it turned out, the results were even more favourable to the Conservatives than the poll predicted, with the Conservatives obtaining 330 seats, an absolute majority.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Ashdown and Campbell were presented with hat- and kilt-shaped cakes (labelled "eat me") on BBC *Question Time* on 8 May.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] With the eventual outcome in terms of both votes and seats varying substantially from the bulk of opinion polls released in the final months before the election, the polling industry received criticism for their inability to predict what was a surprisingly clear Conservative victory.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Several theories were put forward to explain the inaccuracy of the pollsters: one was that there had simply been a very late swing to the Conservatives, with Survation claiming that 13% of voters made up their minds in the final days and 17% on the day of the election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Survation also claimed that a poll they carried out a day before the election gave the Conservatives 37% and Labour 31%, though they said they did not release the poll (commissioned by the *Daily Mirror*) on the concern that it was too much of an outlier with other poll results.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] However, it was reported that pollsters had in fact picked up a very late swing to Labour immediately prior to polling day, not the Conservatives.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] It was reported after the election that private pollsters working for the two largest parties actually gathered more accurate results, with Labour's pollster James Morris claiming that the issue was largely to do with surveying technique.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Another theory was that 'shy Tories' did not want to openly declare their intention to vote Conservative to pollsters – this was the case in 1992, the last time pollsters significantly missed.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] A final theory was the 'Lazy Labour' factor, which claimed that Labour voters tend to not vote on polling day whereas Conservative voters have a much higher turnout.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The British Polling Council announced an inquiry into the substantial variance between the opinion polls and the actual election result.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The inquiry published preliminary findings in January 2016, concluding that "the ways in which polling samples are constructed was the primary cause of the polling miss".
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Their final report was published in March 2016.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The British Election Study team suggested that weighting error appeared to be the cause.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The following table shows final election results as reported by BBC News and *The Guardian*.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] 66 parties are grouped together as 'other parties'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] This column shows the change in vote share percentage from the 2010 general election to the 2015 general election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] BBC News includes the Speaker of the House of Commons, John Bercow, in the MP tally and the vote tally for the Conservatives.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] See About these results, BBC News (30 April 2015).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In this table, however, the speaker (who usually does not vote in the Commons) is listed separately, and has been removed from the Conservative tally.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The UUP did not run itself in 2010; instead, it ran candidates under the Ulster Conservatives and Unionists banner.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] BBC News lists the National Health Action Party together with Independent Community and Health Concern (formerly known as Independent Kidderminster Hospital and Health Concern), which is affiliated with the larger party, for a total of 20,210 votes.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] *The Guardian* lists each party separately.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Health Concern received 7,211 of the votes attributed to the National Health Action Party.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The BBC groups together the votes under the Scottish Christian Party (1,467 votes); Christian Party (1,040 votes); and Christian (698 votes) labels, for a total of 3,205 votes.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] *The Guardian* lists these designations separately.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Guardian lists the vote totals for the Communist Party of Britain, Communist Party, Scottish Communist Party Conservatives, and the designation "Communist" separately.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In this table, these designations are grouped into a single Communist tally.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] One result of the 2015 general election was that a different political party won the popular vote in each of the countries of the United Kingdom.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] This was reflected in terms of MPs elected: The Conservatives won in England with 319 MPs out of 533 constituencies, the SNP won in Scotland with 56 out of 59, Labour won in Wales with 25 out of 40, and the Democratic Unionist Party won in Northern Ireland with 8 out of 18.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Thus the result bore resemblance to 1992.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Conservatives gained 38 seats while losing 10, all to Labour; Employment Minister Esther McVey, in Wirral West, was the most senior Conservative to lose her seat.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Labour Party polled below expectations, winning 30.4% of the vote and 232 seats, 24 fewer than its previous result in 2010—even though in 222 constituencies there was a Conservative-to-Labour swing, as against 151 constituencies where there was a Labour-to-Conservative swing.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Its net loss of seats were mainly a result of its resounding defeat in Scotland, where the Scottish National Party took 40 of Labour's 41 seats, unseating key politicians such as shadow Foreign Secretary Douglas Alexander and Scottish Labour leader Jim Murphy.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Labour gained some seats in London and other major cities, but lost a further nine seats to the Conservatives, recording its lowest share of the seats since the 1987 general election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Ed Miliband subsequently tendered his resignation as Labour leader.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Scottish National Party had a stunning election, rising from just 6 seats to 56 – winning all but 3 of the constituencies in Scotland and securing 50% of the popular vote in Scotland.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] They recorded a number of record breaking swings of over 30% including the new record of 39.3% in Glasgow North East.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] They also won the seat of former Prime Minister Gordon Brown, overturning a majority of 23,009 to win by a majority of 9,974 votes and saw Mhairi Black, then a 20-year-old student, defeat Labour's Shadow Foreign Secretary Douglas Alexander with a swing of 26.9%.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Liberal Democrats, who had been in government as coalition partners, suffered the worst defeat they or the previous Liberal Party had suffered since the 1970 general election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Winning just eight seats, the Liberal Democrats lost their position as the UK's third party and found themselves tied in fourth place with the Democratic Unionist Party of Northern Ireland in the House of Commons, with Nick Clegg being one of the few MPs from his party to retain his seat.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Liberal Democrats gained no seats, while losing 49 in the process—of them, 27 to the Conservatives, 12 to Labour, and 10 to the SNP.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The party also lost their deposit in 341 seats, the same number as in every general election from 1979 to 2010 combined.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The party lost all of their seats in the South West Region, a typical stronghold.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] It was the first time since 1966 (as the Liberal Party) that they won 0 seats in the Region.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The UK Independence Party (UKIP) was only able to hold one of its two seats, Clacton, gaining no new ones despite increasing its vote share to 12.9% (the third-highest share overall).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Party leader Nigel Farage, having failed to win the constituency of South Thanet, tendered his resignation, although this was rejected by his party's executive council and he stayed on as leader.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Northern Ireland, the Ulster Unionist Party returned to the Commons with two MPs after a five-year absence, gaining one seat from the Democratic Unionist Party and one from Sinn Féin, while the Alliance Party lost its only Commons seat to the DUP, despite an increase in total vote share.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The election led to an increase in the number of female MPs, to 191 (29% of the total, including 99 Labour; 68 Conservative; 20 SNP; 4 other) from 147 (23% of the total, including 87 Labour; 47 Conservative; 7 Liberal Democrat; 1 SNP; 5 other).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] As before the election, the region with the largest proportion of women MPs was North East England.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] 111 seats changed hands compared to the result in 2010 plus three by-election gains reverted to the party that won the seat at the last general election in 2010 (Bradford West, Corby and Rochester and Strood).
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] On 8 May, three party leaders announced their resignations within an hour of each other: Ed Miliband (Labour) and Nick Clegg (Liberal Democrat) resigned due to their parties' worse-than-expected results in the election, although both had been re-elected to their seats in Parliament.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Nigel Farage (UKIP) offered his resignation because he had failed to be elected as MP for South Thanet, but said he might re-stand in the resulting leadership election.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] However, on 11 May, the UKIP executive rejected his resignation on the grounds that the election campaign had been "a great success", and Farage agreed to continue as party leader.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Alan Sugar, a Labour peer in the House of Lords, also announced his resignation from the Labour Party for running what he perceived to be an anti-business campaign.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In response to Labour's poor performance in Scotland, Scottish Labour leader Jim Murphy initially resisted calls for his resignation by other senior party members.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Despite surviving a no-confidence vote by 17–14 from the party's national executive, Murphy announced he would step down as leader on or before 16 May.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Financial markets reacted positively to the result, with the pound sterling rising against the Euro and US dollar when the exit poll was published, and the FTSE 100 stock market index rising 2.3% on 8 May.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The BBC reported: "Bank shares saw some of the biggest gains, on hopes that the sector will not see any further rises in levies.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Shares in Lloyds Banking Group rose 5.75% while Barclays was 3.7% higher", adding: "Energy firms also saw their share prices rise, as Labour had wanted a price freeze and more powers for the energy regulator.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] British Gas owner Centrica rose 8.1% and SSE shares were up 5.3%." BBC economics editor Robert Peston noted: "To state the obvious, investors love the Tories' general election victory.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] One (no surprise here) is that Labour's threat of breaking up banks and imposing energy price caps has been lifted.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Second is that investors have been discounting days and weeks of wrangling after polling day over who would form the government – and so they are semi-euphoric that we already know who's in charge.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The disparity between the numbers of votes and the number of seats obtained by the smaller parties gave rise to increased calls for replacement of the 'first-past-the-post' voting system with a more proportional system.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] For example, UKIP had 3.9 million votes per seat, whereas SNP had just 26,000 votes per seat, about 150 times greater representation for each vote cast.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] UKIP stood in 10 times as many seats as the SNP.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The ICO concluded that subscribers had not expressed their consent to receive this kind of direct marketing.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Four electors from Orkney and Shetland lodged an election petition on 29 May 2015 attempting to unseat Alistair Carmichael and force a by-election over what became known as 'Frenchgate'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The veracity of the memo was quickly denied by the French ambassador, French consul general and Sturgeon.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] On 9 December, an Election Court decided that although he had told a "blatant lie" in a TV interview, it had not been proven beyond reasonable doubt that he had committed an "illegal practice" under the Representation of the People Act and he was allowed to retain his seat.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The higher fine for the Conservatives reflected both the extent of the wrongdoing (which extended to the 2014 parliamentary by-elections in Clacton, Newark and Rochester and Strood) and 'the unreasonable uncooperative conduct by the Party'.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The commission also found that the Party Treasurer, Simon Day, may not have fulfilled his obligations under the Political Parties, Elections and Referendums Act 2000 and referred him for investigation to the Metropolitan Police Service.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] At constituency level, related alleged breaches of spending regulations led to 'unprecedented' police investigations for possible criminal conduct of between 20 and 30 Conservative Party MPs.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] On 9 May 2017, the Crown Prosecution Service decided not to prosecute the vast majority of suspects, saying that "in order to bring a charge, it must be proved that a suspect knew the return was inaccurate and acted dishonestly in signing the declaration.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Appearing at Westminster Magistrates' Court on 4 July 2017, the three pleased not guilty and were released on unconditional bail pending an appearance at Southwark Crown Court on 1 August 2017.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The investigation of Party Treasurer Simon Day remained ongoing.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In 2016–18, the European Parliament found that UKIP had unlawfully spent over €173,000 of EU funding on the party's 2015 UK election campaign, via the Alliance for Direct Democracy in Europe and the affiliated Institute for Direct Democracy.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Parliament required the repayment of the mis-spent funds and denied the organisations some other funding.
[src:cambridge/2015-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] It also found that UKIP MEPs had unlawfully spent EU money on other assistance for national campaigning purposes during 2014–16 and docked their salaries to recoup the mis-spent funds.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The **2021–2022 United Kingdom censuses** collectively comprised the 23rd census of the United Kingdom.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses of England and Wales, and Northern Ireland took place on 21 March 2021, and the census of Scotland took place later on 20 March 2022.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses were administered by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in England and Wales, by the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) in Northern Ireland, and by the National Records of Scotland in Scotland.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] These were the first UK censuses for which most of the data was gathered online.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Two of the censuses went ahead despite the COVID-19 pandemic, in part because the information obtained would assist government and public understanding of the pandemic's impact.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census in Scotland was postponed, and took place in 2022.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses in 2021 and 2022 follow on from Beyond 2011, a project by the UK Statistics Authority to assess the value, cost, and alternatives to running a census in England and Wales in 2021.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The project recommended an England and Wales census be held in 2021, and that it be conducted predominantly by means of online returns.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial results for England and Wales were released on 28 June 2022, while initial results for Scotland were released on 14 September 2023.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] After the 2011 census, both the UK coalition government and the main opposition party, Labour, expressed concerns about the rising costs of the decadal census.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] There were also concerns about the value of continuing with the traditional approach adopted for the 2011 census.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] This included whether collection methods were still fit for purpose in a rapidly changing society and whether census outputs, based on a survey conducted every ten years, would continue to meet the increasingly demanding needs of public and private sector users.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Emerging technological developments were seen as providing alternative and improved data gathering opportunities.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] These concerns and opportunities led the UK Government to question if a supplementary or wholly alternative approach to the traditional 10-yearly census was required; more frequent, possibly annual, small-scale surveys could be employed instead.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In 2011, The Beyond 2011 Programme was established to look at alternatives to the traditional census approach.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority coordinated the project which was also undertaken by its counterparts in the devolved administrations of Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Existing census gathering methods would be used only as an alternative, where online methods are not feasible.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] A parallel announcement for Scotland's 2021 census was made by the National Records for Scotland.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The ONS Director, Population and Demography Statistics was reported as saying that an estimated 60–65% of household returns would be completed online.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In April 2014, the British House of Commons Public Accounts Committee (PAC) concluded in its report *Too soon to scrap the Census*, that the 2021 census should go ahead.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] It had reservations over the lack of investigation into the options for using administrative data and encouraged the UK Government to reassure the public about privacy concerns.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Minister for the Cabinet Office welcomed the recommendations for a predominantly online 2021 census for England and Wales supplemented by the use of governmental and other administrative data in a letter to the National Statistician in July 2014.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Under the Census Act 1920, it is for the United Kingdom Government and Parliament to determine the arrangements for census-taking in England and Wales.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Parallel legislative procedures will be required in the devolved administrations of Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] It would be late 2015 at the earliest before regulations were made.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Subject to this legislation being passed the census would be conducted on the same day in England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland to ensure coherence and consistency.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] There is a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] As at 21 March 2021 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, the Census (Amendment) (Scotland) Act 2019 made provisions for voluntary questions about transgender status and sexual orientation to be asked.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Census (Return Particulars and Removal of Penalties) Act 2019 makes the same provision for England and Wales.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The sexual orientation question would also be asked in Northern Ireland.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The campaign 'If you're not religious, say so!' by Humanists UK aimed to change the wording of the census question on religion.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] This campaign encouraged non-religious people to tick 'no religion' in order to create a more accurate portrayal of religiousness in the UK.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Another campaign by the Climate Census campaign group suggested writing in 'Climate concerned' in response to the religion question, to demand climate action from the government.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics published an online guidance titled *What is your Sex* for the 2021 census.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The guidance provided that a respondent should answer according to official documents such as their passport.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Self-identification is already recognised in some countries.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] A gender marker on a British passport can be changed in a less formal procedure than acquiring a legally enforceable gender recognition certificate.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In March 2021, Fair Play for Women, an anti-transgender campaign group against self-identification, applied for judicial review in England and Wales and argued that such incidental self-identification should not be allowed in census-taking.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In the absence of opposition or intervention from any interested party, the judge ordered an interim revision of the guidance.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The government conceded and accepted the order.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The ONS withdrew from the High Court proceedings.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Some academics criticised what they said was the ONS's confusion between the concepts of sex and gender identity.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Other academics supported the design of the census questions, for example, on the ground that the transgender population is very small.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, similar pieces of guidance have been published since the previous census in 2011.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Scottish Parliament also sought to amend the census Act in 2019 to clarify the meaning of sex in that legislation to include gender identity.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The plan was abandoned and changes were instead made in subordinate legislation.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In August 2021, National Records of Scotland issued guidelines regarding the sex question in the 2022 Scottish census.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The guidance states that "If you are transgender the answer you give can be different from what is on your birth certificate.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] You do not need a Gender Recognition Certificate (GRC)".
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority wrote to National Records of Scotland to question the guidelines.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In December 2021, Fair Play for Women applied for a judicial review in Scotland.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Lord Sandison dismissed the case on 17 February 2022 stating that there was "no general rule or principle of law that a question as to a person's sex may only properly be answered by reference to the sex stated on that person's birth certificate or GRC".
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] An appeal by Fair Play for Women was refused by the Inner House of the Court of Session.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority has the responsibility for coordinating the census arrangements across the United Kingdom through the Office for National Statistics (ONS), which is also responsible for the census in England and Wales.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 UK census was the first decennial census in the United Kingdom to include the option of completing the census documentation online.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Across the UK between 15 and 19% of census forms were submitted online.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority proposed that the 2021 census should be conducted predominantly online (with support provided for those unable to complete the census online), supplemented by the use of administrative and survey data and improve annual statistics between censuses.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] For the census in 2021 the proposed target for online completion has been set to at least 65%.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Research has been under way since 2011 to design a new census methodology which maximises the success of an online approach.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Issues identified also included the accuracy of administrative data sets for geographical areas below that of local authorities, problems associated with estimation and the use of address registers.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority has commissioned research strands as part of a census transformation programme which was due to report by 2017 relating to the 2021 census operation, the shape of population statistics in 2021, and the shape of population statistics beyond 2021 in the lead up to 2031.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] A work programme running until 2024, comprising eight phases, was developed by ONS.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Alongside this programme trials of statistics generation using administrative data were planned starting from the autumn of 2015 and running through to 2021 with the aim of ranging across the breadth, detail and accuracy of census outputs.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The contract for preparing, dispatching up to 16 million paper questionnaire packs (for anyone who did not want to, or could not access the census online), and then securely managing, capturing and digitising the responses was awarded to Leidos Innovations UK.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The contract was estimated to be worth around £65.1m.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The parent company of Leidos Innovations UK, Leidos (an American defence, aviation, information technology, and biomedical research company), merged with Lockheed Martin's IT sector in August 2016.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK was awarded the contract for the census in 2011.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Adecco UK was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 30,000 temporary ONS workers who would be working as field staff for the 2021 census.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] An advertising campaign (made under contract by M&C Saatchi) was launched under the slogan of "it's about us" at the start of 2021.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Television adverts tried to show a diverse range of people in various locations in England and Wales in front of a purple fabric screen, with a cover version of The Zombies' "This Will Be Our Year", performed by Jose McGill & The Vagaband, featuring as the advert soundtrack.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) undertakes the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The National Records of Scotland (NRS) is responsible for the census in Scotland.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal was conducted on 7 October 2019 and closed for returns on 7 November 2019 in three local authority areas: parts of Glasgow City, Dumfries and Galloway and Na h-Eileanan Siar.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census was scheduled to take place on 21 March 2021, but was delayed in July 2020 by the Scottish Government because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Scottish Government has come under criticism for the way the census has been conducted, with some news outlets describing the results as being "botched" due to record low turnout rates and failing to meet the set target return rate of 94%.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial turnout rates for the census in Scotland concluded with 79% return rate; an additional round of extension to filling out the census was granted to encourage returns, raising the return rate percentage to 89%.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The return rate for comparison in England and Wales was 97%.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] However national statistician Ian Diamond has said that despite not meeting the target, the census could still provide "really good data".
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The additional round of extension cost the Scottish Government an additional £6m, and £148m in total.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Although it is a Crown Dependency and not part of the United Kingdom, Jersey carried out a census on the same day as the 2021 censuses in England and Wales, and Northern Ireland.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Guernsey no longer carries out a decennial census, instead using the Rolling Electronic Census Project to produce regular census reports.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Isle of Man also undertook a full census in 2021 (having held an interim census in 2016).
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial results, released in June 2022, showed the recorded population of England and Wales to be 59,597,300 (56,489,800 in England and 3,107,500 in Wales), a rise of 6.3% or 3.5 million people over the previous decade.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] This was the largest population ever recorded through a census in England and Wales, and the overall population of the United Kingdom was estimated to be 67 million.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census also showed that the population of the two countries, aged 65 and over, had surpassed the number of children aged 15 and under for the first time, with 11.1 million people aged 65 and over compared with 10.4 million aged under 15.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results of the question on religion were published on 29 November 2022.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The question was voluntary but was answered by 94.0% of the population of England and Wales.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] 46.2% of the population described themselves as "Christian", 6.5% as "Muslim", and 1.7% as "Hindu".
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] 37.2% of the population asserted that they had "no religion".
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Wales, there were more people declaring that they had "no religion" (47%) than those affirming a Christian identity or any other religion.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results on sexual orientation and gender identity questions were released on 6 January 2023.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Similarly to the religion question, this question was voluntary but was answered by 92.5% of the population of England and Wales.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] 89.4% of the population described themselves as straight or heterosexual, 1.5% described themselves as "Gay or lesbian", 1.3% as "Bisexual" and 0.3% were described as having "[an]other sexual orientation" (with the most common being pansexual, asexual and queer).
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] 0.5% answered 'No' to the census question 'Is the gender you identify with the same as your sex registered at birth?' Alice Sullivan, professor of sociology at University College London, reported that in the 16 to 24 age group, 1% answered 'No' to the question.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] She said that females were more likely than males to answer 'No' in that age group, whereas in other age groups females were more likely to answer 'Yes'.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In April 2023, when more granular data became available, Michael Biggs, professor of sociology at the University of Oxford, complained about what he perceived to be anomalies in the data on the 0.5% who identified as transgender, when disaggregated by local authority and other factors.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] He questioned whether the ONS had adequately tested the gender identity question with respondents for whom English is a second language.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Office for Statistics Regulation (OSR), which oversees the ONS, began an examination of Biggs' concerns about the statistics, including the reported result that 262,000 identify as transgender in England and Wales.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] An anonymous government source said they believed the number 260,000 of transgender people was "hugely overstated".
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In September 2024, the OSR removed official accreditation of the gender identity statistics, classifying them instead as official statistics in development.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results for Northern Ireland were published by the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency in Spring 2023.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] National Records of Scotland published the first results on 14 September 2023.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The results showed that Scotland's population was 5,436,600, the highest figure on record but a slower rate of population growth, 2.7% since 2011, than the previous growth of 4.6%.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The first results, in May 2024, were population estimates at output areas, as well as topical data about ethnic group, national identity, language and religion.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The rest of the data was published across 2024 and into 2025.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The low response rates (88%) compared with the rest of the UK mean that the data is only partial so does not fully reflect the state of Scotland's demographics.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census showed there were 2,509,300 households in Scotland with at least one usual resident.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] There were some 930,000 single person households in Scotland and over a third of all households were single person (37.1%).
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census revealed that over half a million people living in Scotland were born in the rest of the UK (563,500).
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Furthermore, that a further half a million were born outside of the UK (554,900).
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The number of people born outside of the UK had increased by 185,600 since 2011.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census showed the population as ageing, with over one million people aged 65 and over (1,091,000).
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The number of people under 15 was only 832,300.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] The majority of people said they had no religion.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Of those who were religious in 2022, 20.4% responded ‘Church of Scotland', 13.3% ‘Roman Catholic’, 5.1% 'Other Christian' and 2.2% 'Muslim'.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] Among those who selected 'Other Christian,' 72,359 people identified as Anglican or Episcopalian.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] In 2022 the census results showed 12.9% of people in Scotland had a minority ethnic background.
[src:cambridge/2021-united-kingdom-census] 77.7% described themselves as 'Scottish', 9.4% as 'Other British'.
[src:cambridge/41-geo-3-u-k-p01] This is a complete **list of acts of the 1st session of the 1st Parliament of the United Kingdom** which had regnal year **41 Geo.
[src:cambridge/41-geo-3-u-k-p01] This session met from 22 January 1801 until 2 July 1801.
[src:cambridge/41-geo-3-u-k-p01] The first session of the 1st Parliament of the United Kingdom, which met from 22 January 1801 until 2 July 1801.
[src:cambridge/41-geo-3-u-k-p01] This session was also traditionally cited as **41 G.
[src:cambridge/41-geo-3-u-k-p01] for permitting bakers to make and sell certain sorts of bread, and to make more effectual provision for the same;" as relates to other grain than wheat; and for indemnifying persons who may have dressed, sold, or used any meal or flour of such other grain finer than is prescribed by the said act.
